## Real-World Case Studies

**Case Study 1 - The Thanksgiving Storm**: During Thanksgiving week 2019, a rapidly developing storm caught hundreds of travelers on I-70 between Georgetown and the Eisenhower Tunnel. Temperatures dropped 40 degrees in three hours, creating icy conditions that stranded traffic for 18 hours. Emergency services couldn't reach many vehicles due to the sheer number of incidents and dangerous road conditions.

Travelers who survived comfortably had prepared for extreme cold despite leaving Denver in mild weather. Those who dressed for departure conditions faced potential hypothermia during the extended delay. The incident highlighted how quickly mountain weather can overwhelm even major highways.

**Case Study 2 - Equipment Failure at Altitude**: A delivery truck carrying ski equipment experienced brake failure descending from Loveland Pass. The high-altitude descent had overheated the brake system, creating a dangerous situation with no immediate assistance available. The driver successfully used engine braking and emergency stopping techniques learned through mountain driving training.

This incident emphasized how altitude affects vehicle systems in unexpected ways. Standard brake performance assumptions don't apply during extended high-altitude descents, requiring specialized knowledge and preparation.

**Case Study 3 - Communication Blackout**: During a winter storm in 2021, cell towers throughout Summit County lost power, eliminating communication for stranded motorists along Highway 9. Emergency services had to rely on visual searches and citizen reports to locate vehicles needing assistance.

Travelers with satellite communication devices received help within hours, while those depending on cell service waited more than 12 hours for discovery. The event demonstrated how communication infrastructure fails precisely when you need it most.

